Detecting Breast Cancer Rate from the Variables

Ching Yi Lam

11/16/2024

1 Introduction

This report focuses on analyzing the outcome of breast cancer by performing PCA, clustering analysis and LOF algorithm. The analysis begins with the description of data, perform PCA and clustering analysis, calculating LOF scores and visualizing their distribution. The goal of this analysis is to evaluate the applicability of LOF in the context of medical data. The report aims to provide insights into the density based anomaly detection techniques can support breast cancer diagnosis.

2 Description of Data

The synthetic cancer dataset has 600 observartions and 11 variables. There are 10 numerical variables and 1 categorical variable. This data set is collected from my professor’s teaching data repository. All of the variables do not have missing value. A detailed description of the variables is given below:

Sample_No: This refers to the sample number.

Thickness_of_Clump: Benign cells are more likely monolayers and malignant or cancerous cells are multilayer. The rating is ranged from 1 to 10. 1 indicates the lowest thickness of clump, and 10 indicates the highest of thickness of clump.

Cell_Size_Uniformaity: Benign cells does not vary in size and malignant or cancer cell vary in size. The rating is ranged from 1 to 10. 1 indicates the smallest size of the cell, and 10 indicates the largest size of the cell.

Cell_Shape_Uniformaity: Benign cells does not vary in shape and malignant or cancer cell vary in shape. The rating is ranged from 1 to 10. 1 indicates the smallest shape of the cell, and 10 indicates the largest shape of the cell.

Marginal_Adhesion: Benign cells are more likely stick together and cancer cells are loose or does not stick together. The rating is ranged from 1 to 10. 1 indicates the cells are more stick together, 10 indicates the cells are loose or does not stick together.

Single_Epithelial_Cell_Size: In benign cells, epithelial cells are normal and malignant or cancer cells are significantly enlarged. The rating is ranged from 1 to 10. 1 indicates the epithelial cells are normal, 10 indicates the cells are significantly enlarged.

Bare_Nuclei: In benign cells, the bare nuclei is not surrounded by cytoplasm and in cancer cells, it is surrounded by cytoplasm. The rating is ranged from 1 to 10. 1 indicates the cell is not surrounded by cytoplasm, and 10 indicates the cell is surrounded by cytoplasm.

Bland_Chromatin: Benign cells have uniform or fine chromatin and cancer cells have coarse chromatin. The rating is ranged from 1 to 10. 1 indicates the cells have uniform or fine chromatin, 10 indicates the cells have coarse chromatin.

Normal_Nucleoli: In benign cells, nucleoli is very small and in cancer cells, nucleoli is more prominent. The rating is ranged from 1 to 10. 1 indicates the nucleoli is very small, and 10 indicates the nucleoli is prominent.

Mitoses: In benign cells, the cell growth is normal and in cancel cells, there is abnormal cell growth. The rating is ranged from 1 to 10. 1 indicates the cell growth is normal, and 10 indicates the cell growth is abnormal.

Outcome: No denotes the presence of benign, and Yes denotes the presence of malignant breast cancer.

A copy of this publicly available data is stored at https://pengdsci.github.io/datasets/BreastCancer/syntheticBreastCancerData.csv.

2.3 Subsetting and Scaling Data

Because the boxplot for all the numerical variables are skewed to the right, we use min-max scaling method to scale all the numerical variables in the dataset.

## feature scaling
breast$Thickness_of_Clump.scale = (breast$Thickness_of_Clump-min(breast$Thickness_of_Clump))/(max(breast$Thickness_of_Clump) - min(breast$Thickness_of_Clump))

breast$Cell_Size_Uniformity.scale = (breast$Cell_Size_Uniformity-min(breast$Cell_Size_Uniformity))/(max(breast$Cell_Size_Uniformity) - min(breast$Cell_Size_Uniformity))

breast$Cell_Shape_Uniformity.scale = (breast$Cell_Shape_Uniformity-min(breast$Cell_Shape_Uniformity))/(max(breast$Cell_Shape_Uniformity) - min(breast$Cell_Shape_Uniformity))

3 Logistic Regression Analysis

The purpose of the logistic regression analysis is to find out if we can use the predictor variables to predict our response variable: Outcome. The purpose of this analysis will be a predictive analysis.

The response variable: Outcome

Predictor variables:

  • Thickness of Clump
  • Cell Size Uniformity
  • Cell Shape Uniformity
  • Marginal Adhesion
  • Single Epithelial Cell Size
  • Bare Nuclei
  • Bland Chromatin
  • Normal Nucleoli
  • Mitoses

Here below we are trying to build the initial model.

  • Build an Initial Model

First, we build a logistic regression model that contains all predictor variables in the dataset. This model called the initial model.

initial.model = glm(Outcome ~ Thickness_of_Clump + Cell_Size_Uniformity + Cell_Shape_Uniformity + Marginal_Adhesion + Single_Epithelial_Cell_Size + Bare_Nuclei + Bland_Chromatin + Normal_Nucleoli + Mitoses, family = binomial, data = breast)
coefficient.table = summary(initial.model)$coef
kable(coefficient.table, caption = "Significance tests of logistic regression model")

The p-value of thickness of clump, cell shape uniformity, bare nuclei, and bland chromatin is smaller than alpha = 0.05. We have significant evidence to indicate that these 4 variables can predict the outcome of breast cancer. Next, we search for the best model using automatic variable procedure to search the final model.

  • Automatic Variable Selection

The cell size is practically important, we will include this variable in the final model regardless of the statistical significance.

In summary, we define two models: the full model and the reduced model. The final optimal model will be chosen between these two models. A summary table of the significant tests is provided below.

full.model = initial.model 
reduced.model = glm(Outcome ~ Cell_Size_Uniformity , family = binomial, data = breast)
backward.model =  step(full.model, 
                    scope=list(lower=formula(reduced.model),upper=formula(full.model)),
                    data = breast, 
                    direction = "backward",
                    trace = 0) 
final.model.coef = summary(backward.model)$coef
kable(final.model.coef , caption = "Summary table of significant tests")

  • Predictive Analysis

We use the final model to predict the status of successful introduction based on the updated predictor variable values for two individuals.

mynewdata = data.frame(Thickness_of_Clump =c(3, 8),
                       Cell_Size_Uniformity = c(5, 7),
                       Cell_Shape_Uniformity = c(7,4),
                       Marginal_Adhesion = c(5, 5),
                       Bare_Nuclei = c(7 ,5),
                       Bland_Chromatin = c(2 ,6),
                       Normal_Nucleoli = c(6, 8),
                       Mitoses = c(7 ,3))
pred.success.prob = predict(backward.model, newdata = mynewdata, type="response")
##
## threshold probability
cut.off.prob = 0.5
pred.response = ifelse(pred.success.prob > cut.off.prob, 1, 0)  # This predicts the response
## Add the new predicted response to Mynewdata
mynewdata$Pred.Response = pred.response
##
kable(mynewdata, caption = "Predicted Value of response variable 
      with the given cut-off probability")

4 Hierarchical Clustering Analysis

We choose hierarchical clustering over k-means clustering is because hierarchical clustering does not require specifying the number of clusters in advance while k-means clustering requires pre-specifying the number of clusters, which we may not be known beforehand.

scales.hierarch = as.data.frame(breast)
distance <- dist(scales.hierarch, method = "euclidean")
# Hierarchical clustering using Complete Linkage
hc1 <- hclust(distance, method = "complete" )
# Plot the obtained dendrogram
plot(hc1, cex = 0.6, labels = FALSE, hang = -1, xlab = "", main = "Dendrogram: hierarchical clustering")
rect.hclust(hc1, k = 5, border = 2:9)

Dendrogram: hierarchical clustering

In this dendrogram, the tree is cut at a height that produces 5 clusters. At a low height, individual data points are grouped into small clusters. At a high height, those small clusters are further merged into larger clusters.

# Figured this out by coloring the labels white to the background
avg_dend_obj <- as.dendrogram(hc1)
labels_colors(avg_dend_obj) <- "white"
plot(avg_dend_obj, cex = 0.6, 
     labels = FALSE, 
     hang = -1, 
     xlab = "", 
     ylab= "Height",
     main = "Dendrogram: hierarchical clustering: No X-Labels")
rect.hclust(hc1, k = 5, border = 2:9)

Dendrogram: hierarchical clustering: No X-Labels

This dendrogram is a simplified version to improve interpretability when the dataset has a large number of points. It retains the hierarchical relationship and the ability to define clusters visually while omitting the potentially cluttered x-axis labels.

4.1 Determination Optimal Number of Clusters

fviz_nbclust(scales.hierarch, FUN = hcut, method = "wss")

Elbow plot: Optimal number of clusters

This Elbow plot above helps identify the trade-off between the number of clusters and the clustering quality. Based on the plot, we would test the clustering results for k = 2 or k = 3 and choose one that aligns better. Next, we will do a Silhouette plot to find out which number of clustering is better for our model.

fviz_nbclust(scales.hierarch, FUN = hcut, method = "silhouette")

Silhouette plot: Optimal number of clusters

The number of clusters for this Silhouette plot is k = 2 based on the peak in the width, meaning the data points are most cohesively and distinctly grouped with 2 clusters.

4.2 Extracting Cluster ID

The above elbow plot indicates that choosing 2 clusters is appropriate. Next, we perform a 2-cluster analysis and extract the cluster ID to add them to the data frame. I chose the variables that have the smaller p-value: Bare Nclei and Thickness of Clump.

hc4 <- hclust(distance, method = "complete" )

6 Local Outlier Factor (LOF) Method: Outlier Detection

To assess the performance of LOF, we need to perform a supervised classification analysis using the variable: Outcome to detect the outcome of the breast cancer. The actual outcome rate pf this dataset is 220 / 600 ≈ 0.3666666 = 36.67%. Any models that have a detection rate greater than 36.67 are worthwhile.

6.1 Distribution of LOF

The distribution of LOF scores is heavily skewed to the right. The results summarize and visualize the distribution of LOF scores are below.

lof.breast <- lof(as.matrix(breast[, c(12, 13, 14, 15, 16, 17, 18, 19, 20)]), minPts = 100)
summary(lof.breast)
   Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max.

6.2 Predictive Power of LOF Score

In the following figure, we choose a sequence of TOF cut-offs and plot the relative improvement rate against LOF scores to show the “performance of detection”.

# We create the ID variable to build our model.
breast$OutcomeID <- as.numeric(breast$Outcome)

# 1 = No, 2 = Yes
## Choose a sequence of cut-offs of LOF scores
cut.lof = seq(1,5, length = 21)
## 
lof.outcome.rate = NULL
for (i in 1:length(cut.lof)){
  ID = lof.breast > cut.lof[i]
  OutcomeID = breast$OutcomeID[ID]
  lof.outcome.rate[i] = sum(OutcomeID )/sum(ID)
}
##
defaultOutcomeRate = sum(breast$OutcomeID)/length(breast$OutcomeID)
rel.detect.rate = (lof.outcome.rate-defaultOutcomeRate)/defaultOutcomeRate
##
par(mfrow=c(1,2))
plot( cut.lof, 100*lof.outcome.rate, type = "l", col = "blue", lwd = 2,
      xlab = "LOF Cut-off",
      ylab = "LOF Outcome rate (%)",
      main = "LOF Breast Cancer Rate")
plot( cut.lof, rel.detect.rate, type = "l", col = "blue", lwd=2,
      xlab = "LOF Cut-off",
      ylab = "LOF and random Outcome rate ratio",
      main = "LOF Breast Cancer Rate")

The above figures show that as the LOF cut-off increases, the LOF outcome rate decreases because fewer points are flagged as potential anomalies. An LOF cut-off around 1.5 to 2.5 seems to provide the best balance between detecting breast cancer outcome and minimizing false positive.

6.3 Tuning Hyperparameter k

lof.breast.50  <- lof(as.matrix(breast[, c(12, 13, 14, 15, 16, 17, 18, 19, 20)]), minPts = 50)
lof.breast.200  <- lof(as.matrix(breast[, c(12, 13, 14, 15, 16, 17, 18, 19, 20)]), minPts = 200) 
lof.breast.400  <- lof(as.matrix(breast[, c(12, 13, 14, 15, 16, 17, 18, 19, 20)]), minPts = 400) 
  #category = as.character(fraud$isFraud)
  ROCobj.lof.50 <- roc(category, lof.breast.50, levels=c("2", "1"), direction = ">")
  ROCobj.lof.100 <- roc(category, lof.breast, levels=c("2", "1"), direction = ">")
  ROCobj.lof.200 <- roc(category, lof.breast.200, levels=c("2", "1"), direction = ">")
  ROCobj.lof.400 <- roc(category, lof.breast.400, levels=c("2", "1"), direction = ">")
  ##
  sen.LOF.50 = ROCobj.lof.50$sensitivities
  fnr.LOF.50 = 1 - ROCobj.lof.50$specificities
  ##
  sen.LOF.100 = ROCobj.lof.100$sensitivities
  fnr.LOF.100 = 1 - ROCobj.lof.100$specificities
  ##
  sen.LOF.200 = ROCobj.lof.200$sensitivities
  fnr.LOF.200 = 1 - ROCobj.lof.200$specificities
  ##
  sen.LOF.400 = ROCobj.lof.400$sensitivities
  fnr.LOF.400 = 1 - ROCobj.lof.400$specificities
par(type="s")
colors = c("#8B4500", "#00008B", "#8B008B", "#055d03")

We can see from the above ROC curves that k = 400 produced the best AUC. This also implies that k as a hyperparameter needs to be tuned based on given data. Increasing the neighborhood size improves the AUC value, indicating better performance. The importance of selecting the right neighborhood size for effective outlier detection for this dataset. LOF is used to analyze this dataset to detect potential anomalies which may represent unique patient cases or data entry errors.

7 Conclusion

This report has provided an in-depth analysis of breast cancer dataset using different techniques: PCA, hierarchical clustering, and LOF algorithm. It underscores the potential unsupervised learning algorithms in analyzing this medical dataset. The LOF shows promise in detecting outlier, the results also emphasize the need for parameter tuning and further exploration of other type of machine learning techniques to improve accuracy in this breast cancer diagnostics.
